mods:titleInfo.mods:title: Dimensions of Internalizing and Externalizing Psychopathology and Suicidal Ideation and Attempts in a Sample of Ethnoracially Diverse Youth

mods:mods.mods:abstract: Suicide is a leading cause of death and a serious public health problem in the U.S., with certain age, gender, and ethnoracial subgroups being at greater risk. Incorporating dimensional models of psychopathology (e.g., Hierarchical Taxonomy of Psychopathology) into suicide prediction models may improve performance and effectiveness of the prediction of suicidal thoughts and behaviors (STBs). Such efforts may be complemented by examining whether dimensional psychopathology and STB prediction models are valid and applicable across diverse identities, as samples in both dimensional psychopathology and STB literature tend to lack diversity. Thus, multi-group confirmatory factor analyses were conducted to assess structural invariance of the dimensional psychopathology model across sex assigned at birth and ethnoracial identity in a sample of substance-using young adults (n = 511). Additionally, hierarchical logistic regression analyses were conducted to examine the associations between the dimensional internalizing and externalizing psychopathology factors and suicidal ideation (SI) and suicide attempts (SA) and whether these associations were moderated by sex assigned at birth and ethnoracial identity moderated the association between. Structural invariance testing results supported partial metric (i.e., weak) invariance of the dimensional internalizing and externalizing psychopathology model across sex assigned at birth and ethnoracial identity. Logistic regression models indicated internalizing psychopathology was significantly correlated with suicidal ideation (SI) and suicide attempts (SA) above externalizing psychopathology; follow-up mediation analyses showed the association between externalizing and SI and SA was fully mediated by internalizing. No significant moderation effects were found for ethnoracial status, indicating the association between internalizing and externalizing psychopathology and SI and SA did not differ across ethnoracial identity. Moderation results showed the association between internalizing and SI were stronger at higher levels of externalizing for females and lower levels of externalizing for males.
mods:mods.mods:note: A Thesis submitted to the Department of Psychology in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.
